tember 14, 2018 |title=Time Capsule: Hollister Jackson |url=https://www.suncommunitynews.com/articles/the-vermont-eagle/time-capsule_57/ |work=The Sun |location=Elizabethtown, NY |ref={{sfnRef|\"Time Capsule: Hollister Jackson\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last=Lightbody |first=David |date=November 10, 2018 |title=Many World War I veterans buried at Burlington's Lakeview Cemetery |url=https://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/news/2018/10/15/history-space-wwi-legacy-lakeview-cemetery/38149359/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |ref={{sfnRef|\"World War I veterans\"}}}}\n\n===Internet===\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.voca58.org/cemeteries/ |title=Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA) |last=Trutor |first=Barry |website=VOCA58.org |publisher=Vermont Old Cemetery Association |location=Burlington, VT |access-date=December 8, 2019 |ref={{sfnRef|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.ancestry.com/ |title=Vermont Vital Records, 1720-1908, Burial Record for Milo L. Bennett |last=Conley |first=Edward B. Burlington (VT) City Clerk |date=November 2, 1921 |website=Ancestry.com |publisher=Ancestry.com LLC |location=Lehi, UT |access-date=December 8, 2019 |ref={{sfnRef|\"Burial Record for Milo L. Bennett\"}}}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://enjoyburlington.com/place/lakeview-cemetery/ Lakeview Cemetery] (City of Burlington official website)\n*[https://www.burlingtonvt.gov/Public-Boards-Commissions/Cemetery Burlington Cemetery Commission], website for the board that manages Burlington, Vermont's cemeteries\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/104091/lakeview-cemetery Lakeview Cemetery] at Find A Grave\n*[https://www.facebook.com/FriendsofLakeviewCemetery/ Friends of Lakeview Cemetery] on Facebook\n\n{{coord|44|29|33|N|73|13|56|W|type:landmark_region:US-VT|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Rural cemeteries]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Vermont]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lakeview Cemetery (Burlington, Vermont)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lakeview cemetery (Burlington, VT).jpg|thumb|Main entrance to Lakeview Cemetery off Burlington, Vermont's North Avenue.]]\n'''Lakeview Cemetery''' is a burial ground located off of North Avenue in [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]], [[Chittenden County, Vermont]].  The cemetery was created in 1867 and dedicated in 1871, and overlooks [[Lake Champlain]].  It is near the current campus of [[Burlington High School (Vermont)|Burlington High School]].\n\n==Details==\nLakeview Cemetery is a non-denominational cemetery owned by the city of Burlington.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  The cemetery's [[Howard Mortuary Chapel|Louisa Howard Chapel]] is available for rent, and is frequently used for marriage ceremonies, funerals, memorial services, music recitals, and other functions.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  The city government's management of the cemetery is aided by the Friends of Lakeview Cemetery, a group formed in the early 1990s to plan improvements to the cemetery buildings and grounds and raise money to carry them out.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n\n==History==\nLakeview Cemetery was established in 1867 when the city of Burlington purchased 23 acres of land from H. B. Sawyer for $3,500 (about $65,000 in 2019).{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  In 1868, the city purchased an additional seven from J. A. Arthur for $2,000 (about $38,000 in 2019).{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n\nThe cemetery was planned in the [[rural cemetery]] style that became popular in the mid 1800s.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  Located at what was then the outskirts of the city and situated near the end of the city's [[tram|trolley car line]], Lakeview included many of the attributes of a park.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  Its narrow, meandering roads, benches, and [[Ornamental plant|specimen trees]] helped make it an outdoor destination for city dwellers, who visited for picnics and other activities.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n\nIn the 1880s, philanthropist Louisa Howard financed the construction of a small church on the cemetery grounds.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  When the stone [[Gothic Revival architecture|Victorian Gothic Revival]] building was dedicated in 1882, it was named in her honor.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  The [[Howard Mortuary Chapel|Louisa Howard Chapel]] fell into disuse during the 1940s, but in the 1990s a group of interested individuals formed Friends of Lakeview Cemetery, which raised funds to refurbish it.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  By 2004, the group had raised $100,000, and the chapel underwent a restoration that was completed in 2006.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  Other improvements and restorations undertaken by Friends of Lakeview Cemetery include construction of a new gazebo in 2010 to replace an original that had fallen into disrepair.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  The new cedar wood gazebo was crafted by hand in the 19th Century [[Adirondack Architecture]] style so that it resembled the original.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n\nLakeview's grounds included three fountains that were donated in the 1870s by John P. Howard (Louisa Howard's brother).{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}} In 2014, Friends of Lakeview Cemetery completed restoration of the fountains, using the remnants of the originals and a photo from a vintage postcard for reference.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n\n==Interments==\nBurials at Lakeview Cemetery include veterans of every major conflict since the [[American Civil War]], including several members of the [[54th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment]], a Union Army regiment of [[African American]] soldiers and white officers.{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}  Several soldiers who served at nearby [[Fort Ethan Allen]] in the late 1800s and early 1900s are buried at Lakeview, including members of the famed [[10th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|10th Cavalry Regiment]] (Buffalo Soldiers).{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n\n==Notable burials==\nMany notable political and military leaders and other prominent individuals are interred at Lakeview Cemetery, to include:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Harold J. Arthur]], Vermont governor{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Warren Austin]], US Senator and first US ambassador to the United Nations{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Milo Lyman Bennett]], associate justice of the Vermont Supreme Court{{sfn|\"Burial Record for Milo L. Bennett\"}}\n*[[Rufus E. Brown]], attorney general of Vermont{{sfn|\"Funerals, Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow\"}}\n*[[Chauncey W. Brownell]], Vermont secretary of state{{sfn|\"Funeral Notice, Chauncey W. Brownell\"}}\n*[[Lucius E. Chittenden]], author and public official{{sfn|\"Death Notice, Lucius E. Chittenden\"}}\n*[[George E. Davis (Medal of Honor)|George E. Davis]], recipient of the Medal of Honor during the American Civil War{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[David J. Foster]], US Congressman{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[George P. Foster]], Union Army officer during the American Civil War who attained the rank of brigadier general by brevet{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Aaron H. Grout]], Vermont secretary of state{{sfn|\"Judge Aaron H. Grout Dies\"}}\n*[[Seneca Haselton]], associate justice of the Vermont Supreme Court{{sfn|\"Many Pay Tribute\"}}\n*[[Joseph D. Hatch]], state legislator and mayor of Burlington{{sfn|\"Funeral of Ex-Mayor Hatch\"}}\n*[[Doc Hazelton]], major league baseball player and college baseball coach{{sfn|\"W. C. Hazelton Dies at Age of 64\"}}\n*[[William W. Henry]], Union Army officer in the American Civil War who attained the rank of brevet brigadier general and received the Medal of Honor{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Oliver Otis Howard]], US Army major general who received the Medal of Honor for heroism while serving in the Union Army during the American Civil War{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Hollister Jackson]], lieutenant governor of Vermont{{sfn|\"Time Capsule: Hollister Jackson\"}}\n*[[Horatio Nelson Jackson]], first person to completely cross the United States by automobile{{sfn|\"More than a burial ground\"}}\n*[[John Holmes Jackson]], mayor of Burlington{{sfn|\"Dr. J. Holmes Jackson, 73, Dies\"}}\n*[[Job Lyman]], Vermont Auditor of Accounts{{sfn|\"The Late Edward Lyman\"}}\n*[[Henry T. Mayo]], US Navy admiral who commanded the Atlantic Fleet during World War I{{sfn|\"World War I veterans\"}}\n*[[George H. Morse]], mayor of Burlington{{sfn|\"Died: George Henry Morse\"}}\n*[[Hamilton S. Peck]], state legislator and judge, mayor of Burlington{{sfn|\"Funeral of Judge Peck\"}}\n*[[Theodora Agnes Peck]], novelist and poet{{sfn|\"Historical Novelist, Miss Peck 81 Dies After Long Illness\"}}\n*[[Theodore S. Peck]], Union Army officer who received the Medal of Honor for American Civil War heroism{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[E. Henry Powell]], Vermont Auditor of Accounts{{sfn|\"Funerals Saturday, Yesterday and To-Day\"}}\n*[[Max L. Powell]], President pro tempore of the Vermont State Senate{{sfn|\"Max L. Powell's Funeral Services Largely Attended\"}}\n*[[George J. Stannard]], Union Army major general whose brigade was credited with breaking Pickett's Charge at the Battle of Gettysburg{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Robert Roberts (American politician)|Robert Roberts]]<ref>{{cite news |date=February 27, 1939 |title=City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48645906/final-tribute/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=7 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts\"}}}}</ref>\n*[[Elliot M. Sutton]], mayor of Burlington<ref>{{cite news |date=March 9, 1908 |title=The Late E. M. Sutton |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48183031/obituary-for-e-m-sutton/ |work=Burlington Daily News |location=Burlington, VT |page=6 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Late E. M. Sutton\"}}}}</ref>\n*[[William J. Van Patten]], businessman, philanthropist, Burlington mayor, and President pro tempore of the Vermont Senate{{sfn|\"Funerals: William J. Van Patten\"}}\n*[[William Wells (general)|William Wells]], Union Army major general by brevet who received the Medal of Honor for heroism at the Battle of Gettysburg{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n*[[Urban A. Woodbury]], governor of Vermont{{sfn|\"Lakeview Cemetery (VOCA)\"}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Newspapers===\n*{{cite news |date=May 26, 1890 |title=The Late Edward Lyman |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40457189/the_late_edward_lyman/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=5 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Late Edward Lyman\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 24, 1898 |title=Funeral of Ex-Mayor Hatch |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42773215/jo_d_hatch_funeral/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=6 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Funeral of Ex-Mayor Hatch\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=July 24, 1900 |title=Death Notice, Lucius E. Chittenden |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40280595/the_burlington_free_press/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=5 |url-access= |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Death Notice, Lucius E. Chittenden\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=March 7, 1905 |title=Died: George Henry Morse |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47662785/died-george-henry-morse/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, Vt |page=7 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Died: George Henry Morse\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 8, 1911 |title=Funerals Saturday, Yesterday and To-Day |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/40457328/obituary_for_dorothy_h_stratton/ |wo