{"title_page": "Markus Oehlen", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Markus Oehlen\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1956}}<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = [[Krefeld]], [[West Germany]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = German\n| spouse        = \n| field         = Painting, Sculpting, Music\n| training      = [[Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n| movement      = [[Neue Wilde]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| bgcolour      = \n}}\n\n'''Markus Oehlen''' (born 1956) is a German [[visual artist]] working in [[painting]], [[sculpture]], and [[music]]. In the 1970s and 80s he was a founding member of the influential [[neo-expressionist]] art movement [[Neue Wilde]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] alongside [[Martin Kippenberger]], [[Markus L\u00fcpertz]], and his brother [[Albert Oehlen]]. \n\n==Biography==\nOehlen studied at the [[Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf]] ([[Alfonso H\u00fcppi]]).{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} His is formative participant of the German art movement [[Neue Wilde]], which was especially active in Germany during the 1980s, and used a [[Punk subculture|punk]] style that stood in opposition to [[minimalism]]. The aim was to attack the high-browed nature of minimalism with a style of painting that is based on instinct and gesturally emphasizes the wild, spontaneous, obsessive and sensual. \n\nOehlen has continuously developed his work and, in parallel with painting, also works on sculptures and musical projects. His new works are increasingly inspired by the perceptual experiments of [[Op Art]], with printed image interferences that occur in grid-like patterns above and below the layers of the picture. Along with forms that are oriented toward computer aesthetics, this brings an aspect of serialism to the images. It can be understood as a humorous and ironic commentary on the expressive nature of painting and \u2013 in retrospect \u2013 on the Neuen Wilden movement itself. Markus Oehlen's complex, layered pictures are composed of a plethora of found images, shapes and distorted painterly elements which, taken out of their previous context, take on a new function and meaning. By rearranging the individual compositional elements of the canvasses in the context of art, Oehlen creates surreal still lifes that were not originally so intended, playing with the notion of randomness and suggesting strange narratives. The pictures on large canvasses convince through their radical approach to painting.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nIn 1977 he meet [[Martin Kippenberger]]. He took part at the group exhibition [[Von hier aus \u2013 Zwei Monate neue deutsche Kunst in D\u00fcsseldorf]] in 1984. He exhibited 1993 at [[The Museum of Modern Art]], New York: \u201eProjects 39\u201c \u2013 with Georg Herold.\n\nOehlen was founding member of the bands [[Mittagspause]], [[Fehlfarben]], [[Flying Klassenfeind]], [[Vielleichtors]], and [[Van Oehlen]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} He played with [[Red Krayola]].  Since 2002, he is a professor at the [[Academy of Fine Arts, Munich]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nHe is the brother of artist, [[Albert Oehlen]].\n\n==Galleries==\nMarkus Oehlen is among others represented by Karma International, Z\u00fcrich and Los Angeles; [[Gerhardsen Gerner|Gerhardsen Gerner, Berlin / Oslo]]; Galerie B\u00e4rbel Gr\u00e4sslin, Frankfurt/Main; Galerie Hans Mayer, Duesseldorf; Galer\u00eda Juana de Aizpuru, Madrid.\n\n==Collections==\nAustria\n* [[Sammlung Essl]] - Kunsthaus, Klosterneuburg\n\nGermany\n* [[Kunstraum Gr\u00e4sslin]], St. Georgen\n* [[Museum Abteiberg]], M\u00f6nchengladbach\n* [[Museum f\u00fcr Neue Kunst Karlsruhe|Museum f\u00fcr Neue Kunst]], Karlsruhe\n* [[Museum Villa Haiss]], Zell am Harmersbach\n* [[Sammlung Frieder Burda]], Baden-Baden\n* [[Kunsthalle Weishaupt]], Ulm\n* [[Bundeskunstsammlung|Sammlung zeitgen\u00f6ssischer Kunst der Bundesrepublik Deutschland]], Bonn\n* [[Museum Morsbroich]], Leverkusen\n* [[Sammlung Alison & Peter W. Klein]], Eberdingen\n\nUSA\n* [[Saint Louis Art Museum]], Saint Louis, MO\n\nSpain\n* [[Centro Cultural Andratx]], Andratx/Mallorca\n\nTurkey\n* [[Proje4L / Elgiz Museum of Contemporary Art]], Istanbul\n\n<ref>[http://www.gerhardsengerner.com/Artists/mo_bio.htm Markus Oehlen - Biography], Gerhardsengerner.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://artfacts.net/artist/markus-oehlen/1609\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20060719133840/http://www.haah.de/english/markus_oehlen/abbildungen.html\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oehlen, Markus}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:German male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German painters]]\n[[Category:Academy of Fine Arts, Munich faculty]]\n[[Category:Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Krefeld]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Red Krayola members]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Markus Oehlen\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1956}}<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = [[Krefeld]], [[West Germany]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = German\n| spouse        = \n| field         = Painting, Sculpting, Music\n| training      = [[Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n| movement      = [Neue Wilde]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| bgcolour      = \n}}\n\n'''Markus Oehlen''' (born 1956) is a German [[visual artist]] working in [[painting]], [[sculpture]], and music. In the 1970s and 80s he was a founding member of the influential [[neo-expressionist]] art movement [[Neue Wilde]] in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] alongside [[Martin Kippenberger]], [[Markus L\u00fcpertz]], and his brother [[Albert Oehlen]]. \n\n==Biography==\nOehlen studied at the [[Kunstakademie D\u00fcsseldorf]] ([[Alfonso H\u00fcppi]]).{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} His is formative participant of the German art movement [[Neue Wilde]], which was especially active in Germany during the 1980s, and used a [[Punk subculture|punk]] style that stood in opposition to [[minimalism]]. The aim was to attack the high-browed nature of minimalism with a style of painting that is based on instinct and gesturally emphasizes the wild, spontaneous, obsessive and sensual. \n\nOehlen has continuously developed his work and, in parallel with painting, also works on sculptures and musical projects. His new works are increasingly inspired by the perceptual experiments of [[Op Art]], with printed image interferences that occur in grid-like patterns above and below the layers of the picture. Along with forms that are oriented toward computer aesthetics, this brings an aspect of serialism to the images. It can be understood as a humorous and ironic commentary on the expressive nature of painting and \u2013 in retrospect \u2013 on the Neuen Wilden movement itself. Markus Oehlen's complex, layered pictures are composed of a plethora of found images, shapes and distorted painterly elements which, taken out of their previous context, take on a new function and meaning. By rearranging the individual compositional elements of the canvasses in the context of art, Oehlen creates surreal still lifes that were not originally so intended, playing with the notion of randomness and suggesting strange narratives. The pictures on large canvasses convince through their radical approach to painting.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nIn 1977 he meet [[Martin Kippenberger]]. He took part at the group exhibition [[Von hier aus \u2013 Zwei Monate neue deutsche Kunst in D\u00fcsseldorf]] in 1984. He exhibited 1993 at [[The Museum of Modern Art]], New York: \u201eProjects 39\u201c \u2013 with Georg Herold.\n\nOehlen was founding member of the bands [[Mittagspause]], [[Fehlfarben]], [[Flying Klassenfeind]], [[Vielleichtors]], and [[Van Oehlen]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} He played with [[Red Krayola]].  Since 2002, he is a professor at the [[Academy of Fine Arts, Munich]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nHe is the brother of artist, [[Albert Oehlen]].\n\n==Galleries==\nMarkus Oehlen is among others represented by Karma International, Z\u00fcrich and Los Angeles; [[Gerhardsen Gerner|Gerhardsen Gerner, Berlin / Oslo]]; Galerie B\u00e4rbel Gr\u00e4sslin, Frankfurt/Main; Galerie Hans Mayer, Duesseldorf; Galer\u00eda Juana de Aizpuru, Madrid.\n\n==Collections==\nAustria\n* [[Sammlung Essl]] - Kunsthaus, Klosterneuburg\n\nGermany\n* [[Kunstraum Gr\u00e4sslin]], St. Georgen\n* [[Museum Abteiberg]], M\u00f6nchengladbach\n* [[Museum f\u00fcr Neue Kunst Karlsruhe|Museum f\u00fcr Neue Kunst]], Karlsruhe\n* [[Museum Villa Haiss]], Zell am Harmersbach\n* [[Sammlung Frieder Burda]], Baden-Baden\n* [[Kunsthalle Weishaupt]], Ulm\n* [[Bundeskunstsammlung|Sammlung zeitgen\u00f6ssischer Kunst der Bundesrepublik Deutschland]], Bonn\n* [[Museum Morsbroich]], Leverkusen\n* [[Sammlung Alison & Peter W. Klein]], Eberdingen\n\nUSA\n* [[Saint Louis Art Museum]], Saint Louis, MO\n\nSpain\n* [[Centro Cultural Andratx]], Andratx/Mallorca\n\nTurkey\n* [[Proje4L / Elgiz Museum of Contemporary Art]], Istanbul\n\n<ref>[http://www.gerhardsengerner.com/Artists/mo_bio.htm Markus Oehlen - Biography], Gerhardsengerner.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\