{"title_page": "Holcombe Grammar School", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = DO NOT COME HERE\n| former_name   = Chatham Grammar School for Boys\n| logo         = Holcombe2.png\n| logo_size          = 220px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.364895|0.520939|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \"Aspire and Achieve together\"\n| established   = 1817\n| closed        =\n| type          = [[Grammar school]]<br />[[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      =\n| president     =\n| head_label    = Principal\n| head          = Mr. Lee Preston\n| r_head_label  =\n| r_head        =\n| principal_label = Executive Principal\n| principal   = Ms. M. Gage\n| chair_label   =\n| chair         =\n| founder       =\n| address        = Maidstone Road\n| city          = [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = ME4 6JB\n| ofsted        = yes \n| urn           = 136594\n| staff         =\n| students    = 420\n| gender        = the school got denied\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       =\n| publication   =\n| free_label_1  =\n| free_1        =\n| free_label_2  =\n| free_2        =\n| website       ={{URL|1=http://www.holcombegrammar.org.uk}}\n| module ={{OSM Location map\n | float = centre\n | width = 250\n | coord = {{coord|51.3831|0.5200}} <!-- Centred -->\n | mark-coord = {{coord|51.364895|0.520939}} | label = Holcombe Grammar School| label-pos = top |label-offset-x = 25\n | zoom = 12}} <!-- marking the school-->\n}}\n\n'''Holcombe Grammar School''' (formerly '''Chatham Grammar School for Boys'''<ref name=letter>{{cite web|last=Diaz|first=Juliet|title=Name change letter|date=16 June 2016|url=http://www.cgsb.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/School-Name-Change-Letter-16th-June.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913161936/http://www.cgsb.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/School-Name-Change-Letter-16th-June.pdf|archive-date=13 September 2016}}</ref>) is a grammar school with [[Academy (English school)|academy]] status in [[Chatham, Medway|Chatham]], Kent, England. It is a selective school. From the 2017-18 academic year, the school planned to become co-educational and remain selective in the lower school. This was blocked - and later approved - by the [[Department for Education]] with co-educational admission desired for the 2018/19 school year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Co-Ed Statement|url=https://www.holcombegrammar.org.uk/2017/01/co-ed-statement/|publisher=Holcombe Grammar School website}}</ref> The school has changed name in advance of becoming co-educational and plans to change all references from \"Chatham Grammar School for Boys\" to \"Holcombe Grammar School\" over academic year 2016/17.<ref name=MedwayCouncil>{{cite web|title=Holcombe Grammar School Admissions Policy 2017/18\"|url=http://www.medway.gov.uk/pdf/Holcombe%20Admission%20consultation%202017b.pdf|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe school\u2019s history is believed to be from 1817, but its formal history began in 1913 with the establishment of Chatham Junior Technical School to train young men aged 13 \u2013 16 for careers as artificers in the [[Royal Navy]] and in the Royal Dockyard School (later College) as engineers. The School evolved to become a centre of academic excellence as Chatham Grammar School for Boys, offering GCSE and A Levels as well as an Advanced Level Vocational Courses. The school moved to its current site in the 1920s, with its premises based around [[Holcombe Manor]]. After 1945 it became a specialist technical school (Chatham Technical School for Boys) and in 1982 it became a grammar school, Chatham Grammar School for Boys.<ref>{{cite web|title=School History|url=http://website.holcombecollege.co.uk/?page_id=23|publisher=Holcombe Grammar School website|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210032500/http://website.holcombecollege.co.uk/?page_id=23|archivedate=10 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In 2016 the school name was changed in preparation for the planned admission of girls throughout the school.  After a consultation with pupils, staff and parents the name \"Holcombe Grammar School\" was selected.  The local authority is now using this name.<ref name=MedwayCouncil/>\n\n== Ofsted reports ==\nIn September 2013 [[Ofsted]] delivered a report on their inspection carried out the previous June. The leadership and management were judged to be \"inadequate\" and as a result the school was placed in special measures.<ref name=\"BBC News 10 September 2013\">{{cite news | title= Chatham Grammar School for Boys placed in special measures |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-24029830| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 10 September 2013| website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 18 October 2015}}</ref> The previous report (2012) stated that the school was satisfactory, specifically because \"students' achievement and the quality of teaching are not consistently good or better in all areas\".<ref name=ofsted2012>{{citation | last=Gaff | first=Robin | title = Chatham Grammar School for Boys | publisher=Ofsted | display-authors=1 | last2=Garrett | first2=Roger|year=2012}}</ref> English, in particular, was criticised as \"although satisfactory, is slower than in other subjects\".<ref name=ofsted2012/> The 2013 report felt that the issues \"have not been tackled effectively\" and emphasised that the quality of teaching had not \"improved quickly enough\"<ref name=offsted2013>{{citation | last=Wellham | first=Anne | title = Chatham Grammar School for Boys | publisher=Ofsted | display-authors=1 | last2=Khassal | first2=Noureddin|year=2013}}</ref> Following a 2014 report the school has now been judged as being \"Good\" in all categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgsb.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/CGSB-Ofsted-report-Sept-2014.pdf|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\nThe pastoral structure of the school is based on three sections: Lower School (Years 7 and 8), Middle School (Years 9, 10 and 11), and the Sixth Form (Years 12 and 13).\n\nThe School Captains Team currently consists of eleven members of the sixth form. The Team consists of a Head Boy, a Head Girl, three Deputy School Captains and six School Captains, who serve from Christmas of Year 12 until the following Christmas of Year 13, or in effect, a calendar year. There are also approximately 50 prefects led by the Head Prefect, who is one of the eleven members of the School Captains Team, along with several senior prefects. Another one of the School Captains is the House Captain and is responsible for overseeing house events within the School{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n=== Houses ===\nThere are four school houses, all named after ships constructed at the historic [[Chatham Dockyard]] located nearby. \n*{{colour box|blue}} ''[[HMS Guardian (1932)|Guardian]]'' \n*{{colour box|yellow}} ''[[HMS Shannon (1906)|Shannon]]'' \n*{{colour box|red}} ''[[HMS Conquest (1915)|Conquest]]'' \n*{{colour box|purple}} ''[[HMS Barfleur (1768)|Barfleur]]'' \nThe houses compete against each other at events like the school's annual summer Sports Day, the autumn Cross Country, sports events such as [[rugby union|rugby]] and [[field hockey|hockey]], and also at tasks like collecting the most 'rewards', to obtain the House Shield trophy.\n{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Buildings==\nThe school comprises several buildings, most notably the former Holcombe Manor. This was extended, replacing the conservatories, then expanded further with the construction of the atrium block, which currently houses the English faculty, opened in February 1997.\n\nDuring the academic year 2001/2002 the school was extended out and up from the old Manor to facilitate English, Drama, Psychology and Music, as old mobile classrooms were removed from the site for refurbishment and a lease renewal.\n\nIn 2002 construction on a new Maths block (\"M\") began. The work was completed in August to be unveiled in the new academic year 2002/2003. This building houses one large first floor room used as an exam room and Sixth Form study area.\n\nIn December 2006 new accommodation for art students was finally ready and opened by local artist [[Billy Childish]]. Consisting of a Skylab-style structure, it was built on stilts above the existing design technology (\"D\") block, and includes a disabled lift, the first in the school.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Art block of Chatham Grammar Boys.jpg|The new art block, and below, the [[Design Technology|DT]] block\nFile:M block of Chatham Grammar Boys.jpg|M block (Maths block)\n</gallery>\n\n==Former pupils==\n* [[Stel Pavlou]], author, screenwriter\n* [[Lee Ryan]], singer-songwriter and member of [[Blue (English band)|Blue]]<ref>{{citenews|title=Chatham's Lee Ryan bidding for Eurovision glory|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/chathams-lee-ryan-bidding-for-e-a74922/|publisher=[[KentOnline]]|date=12 May 2011|first=Danny|last=Boyle}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Smalling]], footballer<ref>{{citenews|title=Chris Smalling: 'Next thing I knew I was meeting Sir Alex. It was a bit surreal.'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/chris-smalling-next-thing-i-knew-i-was-meeting-sir-alex-it-was-a-bit-surreal-2158734.html|work=[[The Independent]]|date=13 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chatham Grammar School for Boys}}\n*[http://www.holcombegrammar.org.uk Official school website]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chatham Grammar School For Boys}}\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Medway]]\n[[Category:Chatham, Kent]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1817]]\n[[Category:1817 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Academies in Medway]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name          = Holcombe Grammar School \n| former_name   = Chatham Grammar School for Boys\n| logo         = Holcombe2.png\n| logo_size          = 220px\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.364895|0.520939|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = \"Aspire and Achieve together\"\n| established   = 1817\n| closed        =\n| type          = [[Grammar school]]<br />[[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      =\n| president     =\n| head_label    = Principal\n| head          = Mr. Lee Preston\n| r_head_label  =\n| r_head        =\n| principal_label = Executive Principal\n| principal   = Ms. M. Gage\n| chair_label   =\n| chair         =\n| founder       =\n| address        = Maidstone Road\n| city          = [[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]]\n| county        = [[Kent]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = ME4 6JB\n| ofsted        = yes \n| urn           = 136594\n| staff         =\n| students    = 907\n| gender        = Boys; co-educational sixth form \n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       =\n| publication   =\n| free_label_1  =\n| free_1        =\n| free_label_2  =\n| free_2        =\n| website       ={{URL|1=http://www.holcombegrammar.org.uk}}\n| module ={{OSM Location map\n | float = centre\n | width = 250\n | coord = {{coord|51.3831|0.5200}} <!-- Centred -->\n | mark-coord = {{coord|51.364895|0.520939}} | label = Holcombe Grammar School| label-pos = top |label-offset-x = 25\n | zoom = 12}} <!-- marking the school-->\n}}\n\n'''Holcombe Grammar School''' (formerly '''Chatham Grammar School for Boys'''<ref name=letter>{{cite web|last=Diaz|first=Juliet|title=Name change letter|date=16 June 2016|url=http://www.cgsb.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/School-Name-Change-Letter-16th-June.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913161936/http://www.cgsb.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/School-Name-Change-Letter-16th-June.pdf|archive-date=13 September 2016}}</ref>) is a grammar school with [[Academy (English school)|academy]] status in [[Chatham, Medway|Chatham]], Kent, England. It is a selective school. From the 2017-18 academic year, the school planned to become co-educational and remain selective in the lower school. This was blocked - and later approved - by the [[Department for Education]] with co-educational admission desired for the 2018/19 school year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Co-Ed Statement|url=https://www.holcombegrammar.org.uk/2017/01/co-ed-statement/|publisher=Holcombe Grammar School website}}</ref> The school has changed name in advance of becoming co-educational and plans to change all references from \"Chatham Grammar School for Boys\" to \"Holcombe Grammar School\" over academic year 2016/17.<ref name=MedwayCouncil>{{cite web|title=Holcombe Grammar School Admissions Policy 2017/18\"|url=http://www.medway.gov.uk/pdf/Holcombe%20Admission%20consultation%202017b.pdf|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe school\u2019s history is believed to be from 1817, but its formal history began in 1913 with the establishment of Chatham Junior Technical School to train young men aged 13 \u2013 16 for careers as artificers in the [[Royal Navy]] and in the Royal Dockyard School (later College) as engineers. The School evolved to become a centre of academic excellence as Chatham Grammar School for Boys, offering GCSE and A Levels as well as an Advanced Level Vocational Courses. The school moved to its current site in the 1920s, with its premises based around [[Holcombe Manor]]. After 1945 it became a specialist technical school (Chatham Technical School for Boys) and in 1982 it became a grammar school, Chatham Grammar School for Boys.<ref>{{cite web|title=School History|url=http://website.holcombecollege.co.uk/?page_id=23|publisher=Holcombe Grammar School website|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111210032500/http://website.holcombecollege.co.uk/?page_id=23|archivedate=10 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In 2016 the school name was changed in preparation for the planned admission of girls throughout the school.  After a consultation with pupils, staff and parents the name \"Holcombe Grammar School\" was selected.  The local authority is now using this name.<ref name=MedwayCouncil/>\n\n== Ofsted reports ==\nIn September 2013 [[Ofsted]] delivered a report on their inspection carried out the previous June. The leadership and management were judged to be \"inadequate\" and as a result the school was placed in special measures.<ref name=\"BBC News 10 September 2013\">{{cite news | title= Chatham Grammar School for Boys placed in special measures |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-24029830| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 10 September 2013| website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 18 October 2015}}</ref> The previous report (2012) stated that the school was satisfactory, specifically because \"students' achievement and the quality of teaching are not consistently good or better in all areas\".<ref name=ofsted2012>{{citation | last=Gaff | first=Robin | title = Chatham Grammar School for Boys | publisher=Ofsted | display-authors=1 | last2=Garrett | first2=Roger|year=2012}}</ref> English, in particular, was criticised as \"although satisfactory, is slower than in other subjects\".<ref name=ofsted2012/> The 2013 report felt that the issues \"have not been tackled effectively\" and emphasised that the quality of teaching had not \"improved quickly enough\"<ref name=offsted2013>{{citation | last=Wellham | first=Anne | title = Chatham Grammar School for Boys | publisher=Ofsted | display-authors=1 | last2=Khassal | first2=Noureddin|year=2013}}</ref> Following a 2014 report the school has now been judged as being \"Good\" in all categories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgsb.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/CGSB-Ofsted-report-Sept-2014.pdf|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Organisation ==\nThe pastoral structure of the school is based on three sections: Lower School (Years 7 and 8), Middle School (Years 9, 10 and 11), and the Sixth Form (Years 12 and 13).\n\nThe School Captains Team currently consists of eleven members of the sixth form. The Team consists of a Head Boy, a Head Girl, three Deputy School Captains and six School Captains, who serve from Christmas of Year 12 until the following Christmas of Year 13, or in effect, a calendar year. There are also approximately 50 prefects led by the Head Prefect, who is one of the eleven members of the School Captains Team, along with several senior prefects. Another one of the School Captains is the House Captain and is responsible for overseeing house events within the School{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n=== Houses ===\nThere are four school houses, all named after ships constructed at the historic [[Chatham Dockyard]] located nearby. \n*{{colour box|blue}} ''[[HMS Guardian (1932)|Guardian]]'' \n*{{colour box|yellow}} ''[[HMS Shannon (1906)|Shannon]]'' \n*{{colour box|red}} ''[[HMS Conquest (1915)|Conquest]]'' \n*{{colour box|purple}} ''[[HMS Barfleur (1768)|Barfleur]]'' \nThe houses compete against each other at events like the school's annual summer Sports Day, the autumn Cross Country, sports events such as [[rugby union|rugby]] and [[field hockey|hockey]], and also at tasks like collecting the most 'rewards', to obtain the House Shield trophy.\n{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Buildings==\nThe school comprises several buildings, most notably the former Holcombe Manor. This was extended, replacing the conservatories, then expanded further with the construction of the atrium block, which currently houses the English faculty, opened in February 1997.\n\nDuring the academic year 2001/2002 the school was extended out and up from the old Manor to facilitate English, Drama, Psychology and Music, as old mobile classrooms were removed from the site for refurbishment and a lease renewal.\n\nIn 2002 construction on a new Maths block (\"M\") began. The work was completed in August to be unveiled in the new academic year 2002/2003. This building houses one large first floor room used as an exam room and Sixth Form study area.\n\nIn December 2006 new accommodation for art students was finally ready and opened by local artist [[Billy Childish]]. Consisting of a Skylab-style structure, it was built on stilts above the existing design technology (\"D\") block, and includes a disabled lift, the first in the school.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Art block of Chatham Grammar Boys.jpg|The new art block, and below, the [[Design Technology|DT]] block\nFile:M block of Chatham Grammar Boys.jpg|M block (Maths block)\n</gallery>\n\n==Former pupils==\n* [[Stel Pavlou]], author, screenwriter\n* [[Lee Ryan]], singer-songwriter and member of [[Blue (English band)|Blue]]<ref>{{citenews|title=Chatham's Lee Ryan bidding for Eurovision glory|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/chathams-lee-ryan-bidding-for-e-a74922/|publisher=[[KentOnline]]|date=12 May 2011|first=Danny|last=Boyle}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Smalling]], footballer<ref>{{citenews|title=Chris Smalling: 'Next thing I knew I was meeting Sir Alex. It was a bit surreal.'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/chris-smalling-next-thing-i-knew-i-was-meeting-sir-alex-it-was-a-bit-surreal-2158734.html|work=[[The Independent]]|date=13 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chatham Grammar School for Boys}}\n*[http://www.holcombegrammar.org.uk Official school website]\n\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chatham Grammar School For Boys}}\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Medway]]\n[[Category:Chatham, Kent]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1817]]\n[[Category:1817 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Academies in Medway]]