{"title_page": "Pepe Pimentel", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{overly detailed|date=March 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2013}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Pepe Pimentel\n| nickname      = \n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Jos\u00e9 G. Pimentel, Sr.\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1929|04|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2013|01|25|1929|04|30}}\n| death_place   = Quezon City, Philippines\n| resting_place = [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan City]]\n| other_names   = Tito Pepe\n| known_for     = \n| years_active  = 1962\u20131987\n| spouse        = Cecila Pimentel\n| children      = Jose \"Joel\" Pimentel, Jr. <br> Isabel Pimentel, Gil Pimentel\n| occupation    = Game show host, actor, singer, politician\n| nationality   = Filipino\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1les Pimentel, Sr.''' (April 30, 1929 \u2013  January 25, 2013), aka '''Pepe Pimentel''', was a Filipino game show host and actor.<ref>{{cite web|author=&nbsp;(philstar.com)|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2013/01/24/900601/former-tv-host-pepe-pimentel-dies|title=Former TV host Pepe Pimentel dies &#124; Nation, News, The Philippine Star|publisher=philstar.com|date=24 January 2013|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPimentel was best known as the host of ''Kwarta o Kahon'', which ran for 38 years, and was considered the precursor and inspiration of popular game segments such as ''[[Wowowee]]''\u2019s ''Pera o Bayong''. He also served as host for the defunct TV programs ''Tawag ng Tanghalan'' (incidentally, he was the first ever champion of the said talent competition) and ''[[Student Canteen]]''.\n\nPimentel also had some notable roles in the movies ''Ang Babaeng Isputnik'' and ''I Won, I Won: Ang S'werte Nga Naman''.\n\n==Political life==\nAfter his show business career, Pimentel served as barangay captain in Barangay Laging Handa, Quezon City (1997\u20132007) and was described by neighbors as very helpful and friendly.\n\n==Death==\nPimentel died on January 25, 2013 in Brgy. Laging Handa, [[Quezon City]] at the age of 83.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1962\u20132000\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[Family Kuarta o Kahon]]''\n| [[ABS-CBN]]\n|-\n| [[Banahaw Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]]\n|-\n| [[Radio Philippines Network|RPN]]\n|-\n| 1965\u20131972\n| ''Tawag ng Tanghalan''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[ABS-CBN]]\n|-\n| 1958\u20131965\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Student Canteen]]''\n|-\n| 1975\u20131986\n| [[GMA Network]]\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''Tayo'y Magsaya''\n| [[People's Television Network|PTV-4]]\n|}\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1963\n| ''Ang Babaeng Isputnik''\n| \n|-\n| ''Fil-American Girl''\n| \n|-\n| ''Dear Eddie''\n| \n|-\n| ''Carioca''\n| \n|-\n| 1965\n| ''Hamon ng Kampeon''\n| \n|-\n| 1966\n| ''The Jukebox Queen''\n| \n|-\n| 1968\n| ''Dos Por Dos''\n| \n|-\n| 1969\n| ''Banda 24''\n| \n|-\n| 1982\n| ''Juan Balutan''\n| \n|-\n| 1983\n| ''D'Godson''\n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''I Won, I Won: Ang S'werte Nga Naman''\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pimentel, Pepe}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino television variety show hosts]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:People from Quezon City]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Radio Philippines Network personalities]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Biographies|date=March 2013}}\n{{overly detailed|date=March 2013}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2013}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Pepe Pimentel\n| nickname      = \n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Jos\u00e9 G. Pimentel, Sr.\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1929|04|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2013|01|25|1929|04|30}}\n| death_place   = Quezon City, Philippines\n| resting_place = [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan City]]\n| other_names   = Tito Pepe\n| known_for     = \n| years_active  = 1962\u20131987\n| spouse        = Cecila Pimentel\n| children      = Jose \"Joel\" Pimentel, Jr. <br> Isabel Pimentel, Gil Pimentel\n| occupation    = Game show host, actor, singer, politician\n| nationality   = Filipino\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1les Pimentel, Sr.''' (April 30, 1929 \u2013  January 25, 2013), aka '''Pepe Pimentel''', was a Filipino game show host and actor.<ref>{{cite web|author=&nbsp;(philstar.com)|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2013/01/24/900601/former-tv-host-pepe-pimentel-dies|title=Former TV host Pepe Pimentel dies &#124; Nation, News, The Philippine Star|publisher=philstar.com|date=24 January 2013|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPimentel was best known as the host of ''Kwarta o Kahon'', which ran for 38 years, and was considered the precursor and inspiration of popular game segments such as ''[[Wowowee]]''\u2019s ''Pera o Bayong''. He also served as host for the defunct TV programs ''Tawag ng Tanghalan'' (incidentally, he was the first ever champion of the said talent competition) and ''[[Student Canteen]]''.\n\nPimentel also had some notable roles in the movies ''Ang Babaeng Isputnik'' and ''I Won, I Won: Ang S'werte Nga Naman''.\n\n==Political life==\nAfter his show business career, Pimentel served as barangay captain in Barangay Laging Handa, Quezon City (1997\u20132007) and was described by neighbors as very helpful and friendly.\n\n==Death==\nPimentel died on January 25, 2013 in Brgy. Laging Handa, [[Quezon City]] at the age of 83.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1962\u20132000\n|